I have already written a bit about <a href="https://www.whitemarketpodcast.co.uk/blog/2017/10/05/making-wmp-open-a-fresh-start-with-the-help-of-mozilla/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">how challenging working open can potentially be</a> in the show's context.

Licensing has always been a crucial yet sensitive topic for the show.Before we dive into the specificities of WMP case in regards of licensing, it might be useful to

Since 2008, WMP (<em>and its predecessor <a href="https://programamarcabranca.blogspot.pt/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Programa Marca Branca</a></em>) has been licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution NonCommercial-ShareAlike.

Since <a href="http://community.oscedays.org/t/why-are-non-commercial-licenses-not-open-source/569" target="_blank" rel="noopener">non-commercial licences aren't</a> <a href="https://freedomdefined.org/Licenses/NC" target="_blank" rel="noopener">really open source friendly</a>, from this point onwards, WMP original content will be licensed under a <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike</strong> licence</a>, also known as CC BY-SA. As previously produced work starts being backed up on WMP's <a href="https://github.com/WhiteMarketPodcast/whitemarketpodcast-repo" target="_blank" rel="noopener">brand new GitHub repo</a>, things such as blog posts will gradually become available under that license. It is the same license attached to Wikipedia content, for instance.

